[2]
Date: Thu 10 Oct 2019
Source: Duneland School Corporation [edited]
https://www.duneland.k12.in.us/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=4&ModuleInstanceID=2325&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=9167&PageID=1


This statement is being released as a joint update by the Porter County Health Department, Duneland School Corporation (DSC), and YMCA Early Learning Academy.

As previously released [https://www.duneland.k12.in.us/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=4&ModuleInstanceID=2325&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=9170&PageID=1], a DCS employee self-reported a positive test for Legionnaires' disease. As a result, DSC closed both the Middle School and Westchester Intermediate on Fri 4 Oct 2019 upon receipt of elevated water testing results. Based on this information, a parent of a child who attends the YMCA Early Learning Academy (housed at Chesterton Middle School) who was having symptoms, had her child tested for _Legionella pneumophila_ on Mon 7 Oct 2019. Today [Thu 10 Oct 2019], DSC officials were notified that test results indicated a presumptive positive for the presence of _Legionella pneumophila_, suggesting a current or past infection.

Based on these test results, DSC reviewed actions taken over the past week to ensure compliance with Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) guidance. Dr. Stamp, Porter County Health Officer (Porter County Health Department), has reviewed the testing of the YMCA preschool student as well as DCS remediation efforts completed on 6 Oct 2019. All remediation efforts demonstrate that water systems are currently operating at temperatures that prohibit _Legionella_ bacteria to grow, thus DSC water systems are safe. Dr. Stamp is confident there is no reason for DCS schools to be closed related to this more recent diagnosis.

Dr. Stamp has further recommended that DCS follow OSHA recommendations to review absence patterns of staff and students. Persons at high risk to or for Legionnaires' disease are those who smoke tobacco, elderly, have underlying lung disease or are immunocompromised. In general, people do not spread Legionnaires' disease to other people.

Students or staff who have recently missed three or more consecutive days at Chesterton Middle School, YMCA Early Learning Academy, and Duneland Central Administration will be contacted to determine if they experienced fever, cough, shortness of breath and headache symptoms. If such symptoms have occurred, affected persons will be recommended to seek a medical evaluation.

Once again, efforts are being coordinated through the Porter County Health Department. Updates will be sent via email to families and staff and posted on the DSC website.

