[The Duneland School Corporation (DSC) is the public school system that serves several townships in Porter County, Indiana, United States (https://www.duneland.k12.in.us). A map showing the location of Porter County can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/Porter+County,+IN. DSC, which serves Chesterton, a town in 3 of the 12 townships (Westchester, Jackson and Liberty townships) in Porter County, closed the Chesterton Intermediate School and the central administration office on 4 Oct 2019 because of an employee's confirmed diagnosis of legionnaires' disease. Westchester Intermediate School was also closed on 4 Oct 2019, because _Legionella_ were found both in the cooling system tower on the roof of Westchester Intermediate School, as well as in the hot water system at Chesterton Middle School.

Within a week of the closures, a 2nd case of legionnaires' disease was presumably diagnosed in a child who attends the YMCA Early Learning Academy that is housed at the Chesterton Middle School. The Chestertown Middle School and the DSC's central administrative center is located on W. Morgan Avenue in Chesterton and the Westchester Intermediate School is located on S. 5th Street in Chesterton. A map showing the location of these 2 schools, about 1.3 miles apart, can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/search/chesterton+intermediate+school/@41.6043292,-87.0646346,15z/data=!3m1!4b1.

Molecular typing of clinical isolates of _Legionella_, if available, can help identify a common source outbreak if the genotypes of clinical isolates match. Molecular typing of environmental isolates of _Legionella_ can help identify the source of the outbreak, if the environmental genotype matches the genotype of the clinical isolates.

It is not completely clear from the news reports above whether legionnaires' disease or Pontiac fever (the non-pneumonic form of legionellosis) has been diagnosed in the child. Legionnaires' disease is uncommon in children. Infected children have usually had many of the same risk factors for legionellosis as have adults. Most reported cases have involved children with malignancies, severe combined immunodeficiency, chronic granulomatous disease, organ transplantation, and prolonged treatment with corticosteroids, or who have preexisting respiratory disease (1,2).

1. http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/965492-overview

2. Greenberg D, Chiou CC, Famigilleti R, Lee TC, Yu VL. Problem pathogens: paediatric legionellosis--implications for improved diagnosis. Lancet Infect Dis. 2006; 6:529-35. - Mod.ML

